				<p>See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ex/20.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ex. 20:6</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/deut/5.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Deut. 5:10</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/deut/7.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Deut. 7:9</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/deut/11.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Deut. 11:1</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/deut/30.16?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Deut. 30:16</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/josh/22.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Josh. 22:5</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/neh/1.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Neh. 1:5</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/dan/9.4?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Dan. 9:4</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/14.15?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 14:15</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/15.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 15:10</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-jn/5.2-3?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Jn. 5:2&ndash;3</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/2-jn/1.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Jn. 1:6</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/13.14?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 13:14</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/42.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 42:2</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/46.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 46:9</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/124.87?lang=eng#86" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 124:87</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-91905_000_012"><a name="-91905_000_012">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote15-91905_000_012">15.</a>
      </span>
				<p>That term was (sh&acirc;ma&rsquo;), which means &ldquo;to hear intelligently.&rdquo; The term was used hundreds of times in the Hebrew Old Testament, as Israel was counseled to <span class="emphasis">hearken</span> to the word of the Lord and <span class="emphasis">obey</span> it.  Different terms were used in some instances in the Hebrew text whenever reference was made to hearing or responding <span class="emphasis">without</span> implied obedience. Examples:  &ldquo;They have ears, but they <span class="emphasis">hear</span> not.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ps/135.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ps. 135:17</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ps/140.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ps. 140:6</a>; italics added.) (&lsquo;&acirc;zan) to give ear&mdash;to listen  &ldquo;I will <span class="emphasis">hear,</span> saith the Lord, I will <span class="emphasis">hear</span> the heavens, and they shall <span class="emphasis">hear</span> the earth.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/hosea/2.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hosea 2:21</a>; italics added.) (&lsquo;&acirc;n&acirc;h) to pay attention&mdash;to answer  &ldquo;Lift up thy voice, O daughter &hellip; : cause it to be <span class="emphasis">heard.</span>&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/isa/10.30?lang=eng#29" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Isa. 10:30</a>; italics added; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ps/10.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ps. 10:17</a>.) (q&acirc;shav) to give heed  Still different terms were employed in the Old Testament when referring to obedience <span class="emphasis">not</span> to Deity but to other people. Examples:  &ldquo;The eye that mocketh at his father, and despiseth to <span class="emphasis">obey</span> his mother.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/prov/30.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Prov. 30:17</a>; italics added.) (yiqq&acirc;h&acirc;h) obedience, to obey  &ldquo;The children of Ammon shall <span class="emphasis">obey</span> them.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/isa/11.14?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Isa. 11:14</a>; italics added.) (mishma&rsquo;ath) audience&mdash;obedience  That link between <span class="emphasis">listening</span> and <span class="emphasis">obedience</span> is found not only in Hebrew, but in Latin and Greek. The word <span class="emphasis">obey</span> comes from two Latin roots: the prefix <span class="emphasis">ob</span> &ldquo;to&rdquo; or &ldquo;toward,&rdquo; and the root <span class="emphasis">audio, audire</span> &ldquo;to hear&rdquo; or &ldquo;to listen.&rdquo; This root occurs in words such as <span class="emphasis">audio, audience,</span> or <span class="emphasis">auditorium.</span> Literally, then, the word <span class="emphasis">obey</span> means &ldquo;to hear or to listen <span class="emphasis">toward,</span>&rdquo; that is, &ldquo;to comply.&rdquo;  The word for <span class="emphasis">obey</span> in Greek, (hupakouo), literally means &ldquo;listen under,&rdquo; from <span class="emphasis">hypo</span> &ldquo;under&rdquo; as in <span class="emphasis">hypo-dermic,</span> also &ldquo;in subjection or subordination&rdquo; and the root <span class="emphasis">akouo</span> &ldquo;hear, listen&rdquo; as in <span class="emphasis">acoustics.</span> In New Testament times, its use was gradually broadened to less sacred realms, including expressions such as &ldquo;children, obey parents&rdquo; (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/eph/6.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Eph. 6:1</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/col/3.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Col. 3:20</a>), &ldquo;wives, [obey] husbands&rdquo; (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-pet/3.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Pet. 3:1</a>), &ldquo;servants, obey &hellip; masters&rdquo; (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/col/3.22?lang=eng#21" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Col. 3:22</a>), and so on.  A parallel pattern is found in the Book of Mormon. Use of terms such as <span class="emphasis">listen, hear,</span> and <span class="emphasis">hearken,</span> written at the time of the Old Testament, generally carried the same implication of obedience to Deity. Those terms in Book of Mormon scriptures written <span class="emphasis">after</span> the earthly advent of Christ were also broadened to include the more familiar usage, as in the language of the New Testament.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-91905_000_012"><a name="-91905_000_012">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote16-91905_000_012">16.</a>
      </span>
				<p>Spencer W. Kimball, &ldquo;We Need a Listening Ear,&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Ensign,</span> (Nov. 1979), pp. 4&ndash;5.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-91905_000_012"><a name="-91905_000_012">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote17-91905_000_012">17.</a>
      </span>
				<p>Steven R. Mecham, president of the Finland Helsinki Mission, personal communication to the author, 26 Apr. 1990. Svetlana&rsquo;s last name is Artemova. The name of the other mother is Raija Kemppainen, wife of Jussi Kemppainen, who at that time was president of the Baltic District of that mission.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-91905_000_012"><a name="-91905_000_012">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote18-91905_000_012">18.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/29.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 29:7</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-91905_000_012"><a name="-91905_000_012">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote19-91905_000_012">19.</a>
      </span>
				<p>For example, see Anne C. Bradshaw, &ldquo;Listen with Your Heart,&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">New Era,</span> Mar. 1989), pp. 28&ndash;31.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-91905_000_012"><a name="-91905_000_012">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote20-91905_000_012">20.</a>
      </span>
				<p><span class="emphasis">Woman&rsquo;s Exponent,</span> (1 and 15 Dec. 1902), p. 52. Earlier, at age 67, she wrote: &ldquo;I look for the time when I will be able to hear by the power of God.&rdquo; (Ibid., 15 Aug. 1888, p. 46.)</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-91905_000_012"><a name="-91905_000_012">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote21-91905_000_012">21.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/2.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 2:9</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/5.41?lang=eng#40" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 5:41</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/36.3?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 36:3</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/23.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 23:5</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-91905_000_012"><a name="-91905_000_012">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote22-91905_000_012">22.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/1-kgs/19.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Kgs. 19:12</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/17.45?lang=eng#44" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 17:45</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/85.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 85:6</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-91905_000_012"><a name="-91905_000_012">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote23-91905_000_012">23.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/5.39?lang=eng#38" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 5:39</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/14.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 14:1</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/33.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 33:2</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-91905_000_012"><a name="-91905_000_012">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote24-91905_000_012">24.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/9.18?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 9:18</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/23.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 23:10</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/9.26?lang=eng#25" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 9:26</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/19.23?lang=eng#22" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 19:23</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/112.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 112:10</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/abr/2.19?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Abr. 2:19</a>; JS&mdash;H, footnote, para. 5, p. 59.</p>
			</li>
		</ol>
                                        
